Type Conversion in Java
Type conversion means converting one data type into another.

1️⃣ Implicit Type Conversion (Widening)
Done automatically by Java

Converts smaller → larger data type

No data loss

Safe

Example:

int a = 10;
double b = a;   // int → double
Order:

byte → short → int → long → float → double
char → int → long → float → double
2️⃣ Explicit Type Conversion (Narrowing / Type Casting)
Done manually by programmer

Converts larger → smaller data type

Data loss possible

Risky

Example:

double x = 10.7;
int y = (int) x;   // double → int (y = 10)
3️⃣ Type Conversion with char
char stores Unicode value

char c = 'A';
int i = c;    // 65
4️⃣ Type Conversion in Expressions
Smaller types are promoted to int

byte a = 10, b = 20;
int c = a + b;   // result is int
Quick comparison
Type	Automatic	Manual	Data Loss
Widening	✅	     ❌	       ❌
Narrowing	❌	     ✅	       ✅